[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1662[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             if not math.isinf(record["backtest_mape"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1663[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             else "inf",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1664[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "backtest_mase":       round(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1665[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 record["backtest_mase"], 3)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1666[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             if not math.isinf(record["backtest_mase"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1667[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             else "inf",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1668[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "disposition":         record["disposition"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1669[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }), indent=2, default=str))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1670[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1671[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1672[0m:[38;5;10m[49m if __name__ == "__main__":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1673[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     run_demo()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1674[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1675[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1676[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Run it with `python supply_forecast_demo.py` and you should see the five-step pipeline complete, a per-segment summary that classifies the gloves and prep pads as smooth, the flu vaccine as smooth-with-strong-seasonality, the orthopedic staple cartridge as procedure-driven, the rare surgical kit as intermittent or lumpy, and the central-line kit as smooth or erratic depending on the seed. Real S3, DynamoDB, Glue, and SageMaker would replace the mocks; the pipeline shape stays the same.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1677[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1678[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1679[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1680[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Gap Between This and Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1681[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1682[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The example collapses many of the platform-grade concerns that the real system has to handle. Here is the distance between this demo and something you would deploy to a hospital's materials-management workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1683[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1684[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real forecasting libraries.** The demo uses hand-rolled Holt-Winters, Croston, and SBA so the example runs in a plain Python environment. Production replaces each with the real fits: Prophet for smooth and seasonal SKUs (with the holiday calendar passed in as the `holidays` parameter), statsmodels' `ExponentialSmoothing` and SARIMAX for the ETS / SARIMA fallback, `statsforecast` or a comparable library for Croston / SBA / TSB, and SageMaker's built-in DeepAR for the multi-SKU pooled model when scale justifies it. The hand-rolled methods miss the annual-seasonality, holiday-effect, and changepoint handling that Prophet handles for free; do not ship the hand-rolled code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1685[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1686[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Glue ETL job.** The demo runs the consumption-prep logic in-process. Production runs an AWS Glue PySpark job that reads multi-source consumption (materials management ledger, OR case-cart system, inpatient pharmacy) from S3, applies the SKU-master successor map, joins the calendar features and the case-volume forecast, and writes the curated dataset back to S3. The Glue job has its own retry, monitoring, and quality-gate logic; failures alert the data-platform team and the pipeline holds rather than running on stale data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1687[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1688[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SageMaker training jobs.** The demo trains models in-process. Production submits one SageMaker training job per (segment, SKU-batch) via the Step Functions Map state, with the per-job container running the appropriate library. Each job's output (a model artifact plus backtest metrics) lands in S3; a downstream Lambda gathers the artifacts and runs the quality gate before promoting the new model version into the inference path.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1689[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1690[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Quality-gate against production model.** The demo treats every newly-trained model as the new production model. Production compares each new model's backtest error against the currently-deployed model's error and rejects regressions exceeding `QUALITY_REGRESSION_TOLERANCE`. Rejected models do not promote; the prior production model continues serving forecasts and an alert pages the ML engineer on rotation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1691[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1692[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step Functions orchestration.** The demo runs the steps sequentially. Production uses Step Functions with explicit retry policies per step, a Map state for the per-segment training fan-out, branching logic for the quality gate and the regime-break handlers, and a CloudWatch-alarm-fed failure topic that pages the on-call team when steps fail beyond their retry budgets. Each step writes structured events to EventBridge so downstream consumers (the materials-management dashboard, the ERP integration job, the per-segment monitoring dashboards) can react asynchronously.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1693[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1694[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-SKU service-level differentiation.** The demo applies the same default service level to most SKUs. Production carries per-SKU service-level targets reflecting clinical criticality: 99% or 99.5% for emergency drugs and life-safety devices, 95% or 97% for routine consumables, and lower targets for non-critical items where over-buying is wasteful. The reorder-point formula reads each SKU's target rather than applying a global value. The clinical-criticality flag is owned by clinical leadership and reviewed annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1695[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1696[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-vendor lead-time distributions.** The demo treats lead time as a fixed integer per SKU. Production carries a per-vendor lead-time distribution (mean and standard deviation, or the empirical histogram) that flows into the safety-stock formula as a random variable. The full formula is:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1697[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1698[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1699[0m:[38;5;10m[49m safety_stock = z * sqrt(lead_time_mean * sigma_demand^2
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1700[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         + demand_mean^2 * sigma_lead^2)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1701[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1702[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1703[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo's `z * sqrt(lead_time) * sigma_daily` is the simplification when lead-time variability is negligible; for vendors with disrupted supply chains, the full formula meaningfully changes the answer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1704[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1705[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cold-start handling for new SKUs.** The demo routes SKUs with fewer than 10 non-zero demand days to a `cold_start_par` model that uses the mean of available history. Production options include: (1) borrow demand from the predecessor SKU using the master successor map; (2) borrow from a similar SKU using item-category clustering; (3) carry a clinical-leadership-configured starting reorder point until enough history accumulates (usually three months). Production deployments also surface cold-start SKUs explicitly to the materials-management team so a human can sanity-check the par before the SKU enters automated reordering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1706[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1707[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Demand regime breaks.** The demo has no regime-break handling. Production carries a `regime_break_calendar` per SKU (or per category) that flags pandemic periods, recall events, formulary changes, and contract switches. The training step either excludes these periods, downweights them, or models them with separate intercepts. Without explicit regime-break handling, training data that includes the COVID-era surge teaches the model to over-buy PPE forever after.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1708[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1709[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Forecast monitoring and drift detection.** The demo emits per-segment metrics. Production runs continuous per-SKU forecast-vs-actual monitoring with alerts on (1) error exceeding tolerance for two consecutive cycles for high-value SKUs, (2) systematic bias (forecast consistently above or below actuals), (3) sudden actual-volume changes outside the prediction interval, and (4) model-output silence when the trainer fails. Without monitoring, the first sign of degradation is a clinician complaining about stockouts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1710[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1711[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical reconciliation.** The demo's lumpy segment uses a trailing average. Production uses hierarchical reconciliation (the `hts` package or a SageMaker custom container running MinT reconciliation) so forecasts at the SKU, category, and vendor levels are coherent. Coherence matters operationally: the per-vendor purchase-order workflow expects the sum of SKU-level forecasts to match the vendor-level forecast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1712[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1713[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Newsvendor-aware order quantity for short-shelf-life items.** The demo computes order quantity via a simple EOQ. Production for perishable or short-dated items uses a newsvendor formulation: the cost of over-ordering (waste, expiry) differs from the cost of under-ordering (stockout), and the optimal quantity is a quantile of the demand distribution rather than the mean. The demo's EOQ is fine for non-perishable consumables; the newsvendor formulation is the correct tool for vaccines, short-dated drugs, and similar items.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1714[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1715[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-facility pooling.** The demo runs per-facility. Production for health systems with multiple facilities can pool inventory across nearby sites. Adding a transfer-cost-aware optimization layer on top of the per-facility forecasts lets the system meet demand surges by transfer rather than emergency order. This connects to Recipe 14.10 (Health System Network Design).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1716[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1717[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ERP integration.** The demo writes to DynamoDB. Production's last mile is the integration with the ERP (Oracle, SAP, Workday, Infor) and the materials-management system. The integration is rarely a one-shot DynamoDB write; it's typically a flat-file extract via S3 plus an SFTP push, an EventBridge Scheduler-triggered Lambda calling an ERP API, or a managed-file-transfer (MFT) integration. This engineering work is often half the project scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1718[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1719[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-Lambda IAM least privilege.** The demo collapses every step into a single Python file. Production has separate Lambdas for the ETL trigger, the segmentation worker, each per-segment training launcher, the forecast aggregator, the reorder-point calculator, and the DynamoDB loader, with IAM roles scoped to the specific S3 prefixes, DynamoDB tables, and SageMaker training-job ARNs each Lambda touches. The aggregator Lambda has read access to the model-artifact bucket prefix and write access to the forecast-output bucket prefix, but no DynamoDB write privileges; the loader Lambda has DynamoDB write privileges scoped to the forecast tables only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1720[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1721[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **KMS customer-managed keys.** The demo references no KMS keys explicitly. Production uses customer-managed KMS keys for the consumption-history bucket, the model-artifact bucket, the forecast-output bucket, and the DynamoDB tables. Each Lambda's IAM role has `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` scoped to the specific key ARNs it touches. The model-artifact key has a separate policy that grants decrypt to the inference Lambdas but not to the ETL Lambdas, which limits blast radius if a credential leaks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1722[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1723[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **S3 lifecycle and retention.** The demo writes to S3 without lifecycle rules. Production configures lifecycle rules that transition the consumption-history and forecast-output buckets to S3 Standard-IA after 30 days and to Glacier after 1 year, with the retention floor sized to the institutional data-retention policy. Older forecasts are still queryable via the history table when needed for audit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1724[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1725[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **CloudTrail and audit.** The demo emits EventBridge events but does not configure CloudTrail. Production enables CloudTrail for all S3, DynamoDB, Glue, SageMaker, Step Functions, and EventBridge API calls, with the trail writing to a separate audit account's S3 bucket. The audit trail is required for HIPAA workloads and for any sponsor-funded contract that includes audit obligations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1726[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1727[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **VPC and PrivateLink.** The demo does not configure a VPC. Production runs the Lambdas, Glue jobs, and SageMaker training jobs in a VPC with VPC endpoints (Interface endpoints) for S3, DynamoDB, EventBridge, KMS, CloudWatch Logs, and Secrets Manager. Required for HIPAA-eligible workloads. The training-job containers also run in VPC mode with internet access disabled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1728[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1729[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** The demo has no tests. Production runs unit tests on the segmentation logic (the ADI/CV² thresholds and the procedure-driven override are the failure-mode-prone core), unit tests on each per-segment model fit and predict path, integration tests on the prepare-segment-train-forecast-load chain with a fixed-seed synthetic dataset, regression tests on the reorder-point formula with hand-checked expected outputs, and continuous-deployment quality gates that run the full pipeline on a held-out facility's data and compare the output against the prior week's results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1730[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1731[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DynamoDB Decimal handling.** The demo handles `Decimal` conversion correctly. The trap is real: every numeric field passed to `put_item` has to go through `Decimal`, every numeric field read out has to be unwrapped before JSON serialization or arithmetic, and `float('nan')` and `float('inf')` are not valid `Decimal` values either. The `_to_decimal` helper above handles all three cases; production code is consistent about where the boundary lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1732[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1733[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Graceful degradation.** The demo treats upstream failures as exceptions. Production has graceful-degradation paths: when SageMaker is throttled, the per-segment training waits and retries with exponential backoff; when the case-volume forecast service is unavailable, procedure-driven SKUs fall back to the historical mean per-day rather than failing the pipeline; when the DynamoDB loader is rate-limited, it switches to a smaller batch size and retries unprocessed items individually; when Step Functions itself fails, EventBridge re-fires the trigger from the last successful checkpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1734[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1735[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational runbook.** The demo has no operational runbook. Production carries a runbook covering: how to investigate a forecast drift alert, how to manually retrain a single segment without triggering the full pipeline, how to roll back to a prior model version when a new fit goes wrong, how to handle the materials-management team's "this reorder point looks wrong" tickets, how to incorporate new SKUs into the master, how to mark a regime-break period, and how to recover from a partial DynamoDB write failure. The runbook is the difference between a 15-minute resolution and a 4-hour outage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1736[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1737[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shape is the same as the demo. The platform-grade work is the difference between a forecast that runs in a Jupyter notebook and a forecast that materially reduces stockouts and on-hand inventory. Build for the operational-grade audit posture from the first prototype; retrofitting it is an order of magnitude more painful.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1738[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
